isher of the Cincinnati Times-Star 50 years","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hulbert_Taft","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"He married his dead wife's niece","body":"Hulbert Taft's first wife, Nellie Phillips Leaman, died in 1927. He then married Virginia Kittredge in 1928 — Nellie's niece, the daughter of Nellie's sister. His third wife, Eleanor Gholson, whom he married in 1946, was a distant relative of Virginia's.","number":1},{"header":"He interviewed Mussolini and Trotsky","body":"As editor and publisher of the Cincinnati Times-Star, Hulbert Taft secured interviews with Benito Mussolini in 1929 and Leon Trotsky. The journalist John Gunther, in his book Inside U.S.A., described Taft as 'the most conservative man I met in forty-eight states.' Political candidates in Cincinnati viewed his endorsements as 'tantamount to election.'","number":2},{"header":"The Taft family owned Cincinnati's main newspaper","body":"His uncle Charles Phelps Taft had owned the Cincinnati Times-Star since 1879. When Charles died on December 31, 1929, Hulbert became publisher — and held the paper for another 25 years, retiring in 1954 but staying on as chairman until 1958, when E.W. Scripps bought it. The Taft family had controlled Cincinnati's newspaper of record from Reconstruction through Eisenhower.","number":3}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"HD3016","display_label":"Both Hooker descendants in American broadcasting — Hulbert running the Cincinnati Times-Star and WKRC; Munson founding Armed Forces Radio Service and Yank magazine.","link_text":"Brig. Gen. Edward Lyman Munson Jr."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Hulbert Taft","first_name":"Hulbert","last_name":"Taft","married_names":[],"suffix":"Sr.","photo_url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f8/HulbertTaftSr-ca1955.jpg"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],